{"key":"post-12448894","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>12448894</id>\n<content>First of all, don't use aluminum.&amp;nbsp; The mycelium will eat through it prior to first flush, leading to bottom pinning due to the fresh air entering through the holes the mycelium has digested through the metal.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Second, the casing layer goes on top, not top and bottom, despite horrible so-called 'teks' to the contrary.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;If you want to case grains, sprinkle the colonized grains into a plastic tray, and cover with 1/2&quot; of 50/50 casing material.&amp;nbsp; When the casing layer is partially colonized, introduce to fruiting conditions.&amp;nbsp; For more information, do a search on 'patching'.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;A better bet for higher yield is to spawn the colonized grains into a bulk substrate material such as compost or manure.&amp;nbsp; When colonized, introduce to fruiting conditions uncased.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next></next>\n<prev>12448863</prev>\n<first>12447117</first>\n<last>12448894</last>\n<when>1272130877</when>\n<utime>04/24/10 08:41 PM</utime>\n</post>"}